- How Lock is Acquired — Step by Step
When a thread hits synchronized (sharedCounter):

Thread hits synchronized block
        │
        ▼
JVM checks: is the monitor on sharedCounter FREE?
        │
   ┌────┴────┐
  YES        NO
   │          │
   ▼          ▼
Thread      Thread goes into
ACQUIRES    BLOCKED state
the lock    (OS suspends it)
   │          │
   ▼          └──► waits until lock is FREE
Executes         then competes again
the block
   │
   ▼
Lock RELEASED automatically
when block exits

- What Happens to the Blocked Thread
  When Thread1 holds the lock and Thread2 is blocked:

Thread2 state machine:

RUNNABLE ──► hits synchronized ──► lock taken ──► BLOCKED
                                                      │
                                          OS suspends Thread2
                                          (not using CPU at all)
                                                      │
                                          Thread1 exits block
                                          MONITOREXIT fires
                                                      │
                                          JVM notifies OS
                                          Thread2 becomes RUNNABLE
                                                      │
                                          Thread2 competes for lock again
                                          (if no other thread grabs it first)
                                                      │
                                          Thread2 ACQUIRES lock ──► executes

- Every object has a built-in monitor lock — we don't create it
- synchronized block → compiler inserts MONITORENTER / MONITOREXIT bytecode
- Lock is always auto-released when the block exits (normal or exception)
- Blocked thread is managed by OS + JVM — woken up automatically when lock is free
- notify/wait is only needed when a thread must pause for a business condition, not just for mutual exclusion